addCraftRecipe.description:
Creates an unshaped crafting recipe.

Ingredients should have a continuous 1D array like this:
```
[id, count, damage, id, count, damage, id, count, damage, ...]
```
addCraftRecipe.example:
```
Item.addCraftRecipe(256, 1, 0, [1, 1, 0, 2, 1, 0]);
```
This creates a shovel from 1 stone block & 1 grass block.

addFurnaceRecipe.example:
```
Item.addFurnaceRecipe(1, 4, 0);
```
Creates a furnace recipe to make cobblestone from stone.

addShapedRecipe.description: Adds a shaped crafting recipe. Use this function if you want your recipe to be in a specific shape.
addShapedRecipe.example:
This makes you receive 64 stone from a crafting recipe of grass blocks shaped in a diamond.
```
Item.addShapedRecipe(1, 64, 0, [
  " x ", // Top row.
  "x x", // Middle row.
  " x " // Bottom row.
], ["x", 2, 0]); // This makes "x" mean grass (2) with damage of (0).
```
Here is an example of what it looks like in game:

![picture of crafting recipe](images/shapedrecipe1.png)


This makes you receive 64 stone from a crafting recipe of grass blocks shaped in a diamond, with a bedrock block in the center.
```
Item.addShapedRecipe(1, 64, 0, [
  " x ", // Top row.
  "xbx", // Middle row.
  " x " // Bottom row.
], ["x", 2, 0, "b", 7, 0]); // This makes "x" mean grass (2) with damage of (0).
// Also makes "b" mean bedrock (7) with damage of (0).
```
Here is an example of what it looks like in game:

![picture of crafting recipe](images/shapedrecipe2.png)

defineLiquidBlock.args: int, string, array OR string, int
defineLiquidBlock.description:
Defines a new liquid block.

`id + 1` will be used as the stationary version's ID.

Returns `id + 1`
defineLiquidBlock.example:
```
var liquidId = 191; // 192 will be used for still version
Block.defineLiquidBlock(liquidId, "Mudslide", [["stone", 0], ["sand", 0]], 10); // 10 = lava
```

defineBlock.args: int, string, array OR string, int, bool, int
defineBlock.arg_names: id, name, textures, material, opaque, renderType
defineBlock.description:
Defines a new block These are the parameters in order:
- `id`: The block ID.
- `name`: The name of the block.
- `textures`: The name of a texture, or a texture matrix.

**Note**: You can find texture names [here, on zhuowei's site.](http://zhuoweizhang.net/mcpetexturenames/)
Example of a texture matrix:
```
[["bottom texture", subID], ["top texture", subID], ["south texture", subID], ["north texture", subID], ["west texture", subID], ["east texture name", subID]]
```
- `material`: Use a block's material for this one.
- `opaque`: ???
- `renderType`: Sets the render type this block will use.

getAllBlockIds.description: Returns an aray of all used block IDs.

getDestroyTime.description: Returns the destroy time of a block.

getFriction.description:
Returns the amount of friction a block has. The higher the friction, the slower the player walks over them.

All blocks return `0.6`, except ice which returns `0.98`.

getRenderType.description: Returns the render type being used by the block.

setColor.description:
Changes the color of the block.

Replace `#` with `0x`, and wrap it inside an array.
setColor.example:
For instance, if I want to make my custom block pink (#ff00ff):
```
Block.setColor(204, [0xff00ff]);
```

setDestroyTime.description:
Sets how long to destroy a block. A shorter time means a lesser time required.
Time is not in seconds. See the MC wiki for examples, [specifically the 'Breaking time' by hand column](http://minecraft.gamepedia.com/Breaking#Blocks_by_hardness).

setExplosionResistance.description:
Sets the explosion resistance of a single block.
`resistance` is the total number of TNT explosions it will take to destroy the block.

setFriction.description:
Sets the friction of a block. The higher the friction, the slower the player walks over them.

All blocks have `0.6`, except ice which has `0.98`.

setLightLevel.description:
Sets how much light this block will give off.
`lightLevel` must be from 0-15.

setLightOpacity.description:
Sets the light opacity of a block. You can use it for letting light through.
- 0 lets all light through.
- 10 (max) lets none through.
You may have to use `Block.setRenderLayer(YOUR_ID_HERE, 4);`, which sets a block's render layer to 4 (plants), in order for the light to pass through.

setRedstoneConsumer.description: Allows a block to accept redstone input.

setRenderLayer.description: Sets the layer this block will render at.

setRenderType.description: Sets the rendering type of this block.

setShape.args: int, double, double, double, double, double, double, int
setShape.arg_names: id, minX, minY, minZ, maxX, maxY, maxZ, damage
setShape.example:
```
Block.setShape(204, 0.25, 0, 0.25, 0.75, 0.5, 0.75, 0);
```
This creates a block that is half the size of a regular block. Do note, with the full light opacity, blocks may not let light through.

![picture of custom shape](images/setshape_example.png)
